# **2. Goals ****&**** Success Metrics**

## **2.1 Business Goals**

- Achieve 250,000 monthly active users (MAU) within 12 months of launch

- Attain a Day-30 retention rate of 45%+ through proactive, high-value prompts

- Generate revenue via freemium subscription (Basic free, Premium at $9.99/month)

- Establish data partnerships with major financial institutions for deeper integration

- Build trust through best-in-class data security and privacy practices

## **2.2 User Goals**

- Understand their complete financial picture in one place, at a glance

- Know exactly how much discretionary money they have available right now

- Never be surprised by a forgotten bill, subscription renewal, or large upcoming expense

- Receive actionable, personalized guidance rather than raw data dumps

- Feel in control of their money without spending hours on manual tracking

## **2.3 Key Success Metrics (KPIs)**

| **Metric** | **Definition** | **Target (12-month)** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| MAU | Users active at least once in 30 days | 250,000 |
| D30 Retention | Users returning at Day 30 | 45% |
| Connected Accounts / User | Avg. financial accounts linked | >3.5 |
| Email Integration Rate | % of users who connect email | 60% |
| Prompt Engagement Rate | % of prompts acted upon by user | >35% |
| Premium Conversion | Free-to-paid conversion rate | 12% |
| NPS | Net Promoter Score | >50 |
| App Store Rating | Average star rating | 4.5+ |

# **3. Target Users ****&**** Personas**

## **3.1 Primary Personas**

### **Persona 1 — The Busy Professional (****"****Maya****"****)**

- Age 32, software engineer, earns $140K/year

- Has checking, savings, 2 credit cards, 401(k), and a student loan

- Pain: Loses track of subscriptions, overspends on dining, misses investment rebalancing cues

- Goal: Wants a single app that tells her what she can spend on dinner tonight without guilt

### **Persona 2 — The Young Family (****"****David ****&**** Priya****"****)**

- Ages 35/33, combined income $185K, two kids, mortgage, car loan, college savings

- Pain: Variable monthly expenses make budgeting hard; surprise expenses derail savings

- Goal: Shared financial visibility with smart alerts before expenses hit

### **Persona 3 — The Near-Retiree (****"****Robert****"****)**

- Age 58, managing multiple investment accounts, pension, rental income, insurance

- Pain: Hard to track withdrawal strategies, required minimum distributions, portfolio drift

- Goal: Clean cash flow picture that factors in all income and investment activity

## **3.2 Out-of-Scope Users (v1.0)**

- Small businesses or freelancers with complex business accounting needs

- Users in countries without supported bank aggregator coverage

- Minors under 18

# **4. Integrations ****&**** Data Sources**

## **4.1 Financial Account Integrations**

FinFlow connects to financial institutions via certified open-banking aggregators (Plaid, MX, Finicity) as primary providers, with direct bank API partnerships as a secondary layer for major institutions.

### **4.1.1 Banking**

- Checking accounts: real-time balance, transaction history, pending transactions

- Savings accounts: balance, interest earned, scheduled transfers

- Money market accounts: balance and yield data

- Supported institutions: 12,000+ banks and credit unions via aggregators

- Refresh cadence: real-time webhooks where available, polling every 4 hours as fallback

### **4.1.2 Credit Cards**

- Current balance, available credit, and credit utilization

- Statement balance, minimum payment, and due date (critical for prompt engine)

- Full itemized transaction feed with merchant name, category, and amount

- Rewards points / cashback balance tracking

- Interest rate (APR) for debt payoff modeling

### **4.1.3 Loans**

- Mortgage: outstanding balance, monthly payment, escrow details, next due date

- Auto loans: balance, monthly payment, payoff date

- Student loans: federal and private; servicer integration; income-driven repayment tracking

- Personal loans: balance, rate, and payment schedule

- HELOC: credit line, balance, draw period status

### **4.1.4 Investments**

- Brokerage accounts: holdings, performance, realized/unrealized gains

- Retirement accounts: 401(k), IRA, Roth IRA — balance, contribution YTD, employer match tracking

- 529 college savings plans

- Crypto wallets: read-only balance tracking (Coinbase, Kraken, Ledger via APIs)

- Real estate: Zestimate / manual entry for net worth calculation

- Market data: EOD pricing via integrated market data provider

### **4.1.5 Other Financial Instruments**

- Insurance policies: premium amounts and due dates (home, auto, life, health)

- Utility accounts: bill amounts and due dates where APIs are available

- PayPal / Venmo / Cash App: balance and transaction history

- HSA / FSA accounts: balance, eligible expenses, rollover deadlines

## **4.2 Email Integration**

Email integration is a core and differentiating feature of FinFlow. With explicit user consent, FinFlow connects to Gmail and Outlook (OAuth 2.0) and scans email for financial signals.

Privacy guarantee: FinFlow does not read, store, or transmit the content of personal email. It uses on-device NLP pattern matching and server-side processing only on emails matching financial filters. Users may revoke access at any time.

| **Email Signal Type** | **What FinFlow Extracts** |
| --- | --- |
| Purchase receipts / order confirmations | Merchant, amount, date — cross-referenced with card transactions |
| Subscription billing notices | Service name, amount, billing date — added to upcoming expenses |
| Utility & service bills | Provider, amount due, due date |
| Loan & credit card statements | Due date, minimum payment, full balance |
| Insurance renewal notices | Provider, premium, renewal date |
| Travel itineraries (flights, hotels) | Trip dates, estimated costs, booking confirmations |
| Tax documents (W-2, 1099, refund notices) | Document type, issuer — alerts user to review |
| Bank fraud alerts / balance notifications | Alert type — surfaced in FinFlow notification center |
| Salary / payroll deposit notifications | Expected pay date, estimated amount |

# **5. Feature Requirements**

## **5.1 Unified Financial Dashboard**

The Dashboard is the home screen — a real-time snapshot of the user's complete financial health.

### **5.1.1 Net Worth Module**

- Displays total assets minus total liabilities, updated daily

- Assets: cash + investments + real estate + other assets

- Liabilities: credit card balances + loans + HELOC

- Trend sparkline: 30-day, 90-day, 1-year net worth trajectory

- Drill-down by asset class or liability type

### **5.1.2 Account Summary Cards**

- Individual card per linked account showing current balance and last-updated timestamp

- Color-coded status: green (positive), amber (approaching limit or low balance), red (overdue)

- Tap to drill into full transaction history for that account

- Sorting: by type, by balance, by last activity

## **5.2 Income ****&**** Spend Identification and Categorization**

### **5.2.1 Transaction Ingestion**

- All transactions across connected accounts ingested in near-real-time

- Merchant name normalization ("SQ *BLUE BOTTLE" becomes "Blue Bottle Coffee")

- Duplicate detection across accounts (e.g., debit card charge + bank debit for same purchase)

- Manual transaction entry for cash purchases

### **5.2.2 Automatic Categorization**

- ML-based classifier trained on 50M+ anonymized financial transactions

- Primary categories: Income, Housing, Food & Dining, Transportation, Healthcare, Entertainment, Shopping, Travel, Personal Care, Education, Giving, Taxes, Savings & Investments, Transfers

- Sub-categories (e.g., Food & Dining > Restaurants, Groceries, Coffee Shops, Delivery)

- Confidence score per categorization; low-confidence items flagged for user review

- User can override any categorization; corrections feed back to personalize the model

- Split transactions: user can allocate one transaction across multiple categories

- Recurring transaction detection: identifies and labels repeating charges (subscriptions, rent, payroll)

### **5.2.3 Income Detection**

- Distinguishes between active income (payroll, freelance), passive income (dividends, rental), and transfers

- Payroll deposits: links to email pay stubs when available for gross pay, deductions, and net pay

- Variable income smoothing: for freelancers, calculates 3-month trailing average

- Expected vs. actual income alerts: notifies user if expected paycheck is late or differs from expected amount

## **5.3 Cash Flow Analysis**

### **5.3.1 Cash Flow Dashboard**

- Monthly in/out bar chart: income vs. total spend with net surplus/deficit

- Weekly and daily granularity views

- Rolling 30-day cash position across all liquid accounts

- Fixed vs. variable expense breakdown

- Year-over-year and month-over-month comparisons

### **5.3.2 Projected Cash Flow**

- Forward-looking 30/60/90-day cashflow projection

- Incorporates: known recurring income (payroll, rent received), confirmed upcoming bills (from email + statement data), estimated recurring variable spend (based on past 3 months average), and scheduled loan/credit card payments

- Confidence band shown on projection (tight for well-established users, wider for new users)

- User can manually add expected income or expense to refine the projection

## **5.4 Allowable Expense Prompting**

This is a key differentiating feature. Rather than simply showing historical data, FinFlow tells users what they can safely spend right now.

### **5.4.1 Spend Budget Prompt**

- Based on current liquid balance, confirmed upcoming fixed expenses (next 30 days), projected variable needs (food, transport), and user-defined savings goal contribution — FinFlow calculates a real-time "Safe to Spend" amount

- Safe to Spend is displayed prominently on the dashboard and updated in real-time as transactions occur

- Breakdown: Total liquid balance minus upcoming committed expenses minus savings buffer equals discretionary available

- Category-level prompts: "You have $180 left for dining this month" based on user's target or historical pattern

### **5.4.2 In-the-Moment Spend Check**

- User can ask "Can I afford [amount]?" via a quick-check widget

- FinFlow responds with yes/no and impact: "Yes — spending $200 today reduces your safe-to-spend to $320 and still covers all bills through the 30th"

- Optional: Apple Watch / widget integration for glanceable Safe to Spend balance

### **5.4.3 Spend Goal Guardrails**

- Users set optional monthly targets per category

- FinFlow warns at 75% and 90% of each target

- Post-month summary: actual vs. target per category with trend

## **5.5 Upcoming Expense Intelligence**

This module combines email signals, past transaction patterns, and calendar awareness to surface upcoming expenses the user may not be actively tracking.

### **5.5.1 Known Upcoming Bills (Email-Sourced)**

- FinFlow scans email for bill notices, subscription renewals, and due date reminders

- Surfaces these as structured upcoming expense cards: merchant, amount, due date, and payment method

- Allows user to confirm, edit amount (if variable), or mark as "already handled"

- Subscription audit: lists all detected subscriptions with amounts; allows user to flag any for cancellation review

### **5.5.2 Predicted Upcoming Expenses (Pattern-Based)**

- Recurring charge detection: if the same merchant has charged monthly for 3+ months, FinFlow schedules a predicted future charge

- Annual charges predicted: insurance premiums, Amazon Prime, domain renewals, etc. predicted 30 days in advance based on prior-year transaction

- Seasonal spend alerts: "Based on last year, you typically spend $600+ on gifts in December. You're currently on track to exceed that."

- Car registration, tax season, back-to-school — calendar-triggered contextual prompts based on historical behavior

### **5.5.3 Travel ****&**** Event Expense Planning**

- Email-detected travel bookings (flights, hotels, car rentals) are added to upcoming expenses

- FinFlow estimates ancillary travel spend (meals, transport, activities) based on destination and trip length, using historical travel spend patterns

- Creates a temporary "trip budget" card with running spend vs. estimate during travel dates

### **5.5.4 Upcoming Expense Timeline View**

- Calendar / timeline view showing all upcoming expenses for the next 90 days

- Color-coded by confidence: confirmed (from statement/email), predicted high confidence, predicted low confidence

- Stacked view showing impact on projected cash position

## **5.6 Notifications ****&**** Proactive Prompts**

FinFlow's notification system is designed to be high-signal and low-noise. Users control frequency and channels.

### **Prompt Types**

- Bill due in 3 days — "Your Comcast bill of $89 is due Thursday. Pay from Checking (balance: $2,140)?"

- Low balance warning — "Your checking balance drops below $500 on Oct 18 based on scheduled payments."

- Unusual spend — "You've spent $340 on dining this week, 2x your typical weekly average."

- Subscription detected — "We found a new $14.99/month charge to Paramount+. Add to your expense tracker?"

- Income received — "$5,200 payroll deposit from Acme Corp received. Your Safe to Spend is now $1,840."

- Savings opportunity — "You have $600 above your 30-day expense buffer. Consider moving it to your high-yield savings."

- Annual expense approaching — "Your car insurance renewed last October for $1,240. It's likely due in 3 weeks."

# **6. Non-Functional Requirements**

## **6.1 Security ****&**** Privacy**

- Bank-grade 256-bit AES encryption at rest; TLS 1.3 in transit

- No storage of banking credentials — OAuth tokens only, managed via aggregator

- Email: OAuth 2.0 access with read-only scopes; no email content stored on servers beyond extracted financial metadata

- SOC 2 Type II compliance required at launch

- GDPR and CCPA compliant: full data export and deletion on request within 30 days

- Biometric authentication (Face ID / fingerprint) required for app access

- Session timeout after 10 minutes of inactivity; configurable

- Fraud detection on login: anomalous IP/device triggers step-up authentication

- Penetration testing quarterly; third-party security audit annually

## **6.2 Performance**

- App cold start: under 2 seconds on supported devices

- Dashboard load (cached data): under 500ms

- Account refresh (full sync): under 30 seconds for typical user (< 10 accounts)

- Email scan: background process, complete within 5 minutes of email connection or new email arrival

- Notification delivery latency: under 60 seconds from trigger event

- API uptime SLA: 99.9% (< 8.7 hours downtime per year)

## **6.3 Scalability**

- Architecture: cloud-native, microservices on AWS (primary) with multi-region active-passive failover

- Horizontal auto-scaling for data ingestion and categorization workers

- Support 5M users without architecture re-design

- Database: sharded PostgreSQL with read replicas for transaction history; Redis for real-time balance caching

## **6.4 Accessibility**

- WCAG 2.1 AA compliance on web and mobile

- Dynamic type support (iOS) and font scaling (Android)

- Screen reader compatible (VoiceOver / TalkBack) for all core flows

- Color-blind accessible palette — no information conveyed by color alone

# **7. User Experience Principles**

- Clarity over completeness: Show the user what they need to act on, not everything we know

- Proactive, not reactive: FinFlow should tell users things before they think to ask

- Earn trust incrementally: Show value immediately; ask for more permissions only when the payoff is clear

- Reduce cognitive load: Complex financial data surfaced as simple, human answers ("You can spend $120 on dinner")

- Respect attention: Maximum 2 push notifications per day unless user opts for more; smart suppression during do-not-disturb hours

- Graceful degradation: If an account connection fails, make it clearly visible but don't break the rest of the experience

## **7.1 Onboarding Flow**

- Welcome & value proposition (30-second explainer)

- Account creation: email + password + biometric enrollment

- Connect first financial account (bank checking recommended)

- First value moment: dashboard loads with real balance and recent transactions

- Permission prompt: "Connect email to unlock upcoming expense detection"

- Connect additional accounts (skippable; resurface later)

- Personalization: set monthly savings goal and 1–2 spending priorities

# **8. Technical Architecture Overview**

## **8.1 System Components**

| **Component** | **Description** |
| --- | --- |
| Mobile Apps (iOS / Android) | React Native with native modules for biometrics and background sync |
| Web App | React + TypeScript, server-side rendered for performance |
| API Gateway | GraphQL gateway with REST fallback; rate-limited per user |
| Auth Service | OAuth 2.0 / OIDC with JWT; MFA support |
| Account Aggregation Service | Plaid / MX integration layer; manages token refresh and webhook ingestion |
| Email Integration Service | Gmail & Outlook OAuth; on-device NLP pre-filter + server NLP extraction pipeline |
| Transaction Processor | Ingestion → deduplication → normalization → ML categorization pipeline |
| Cashflow Engine | Projection model combining actuals, scheduled, and predicted transactions |
| Prompt Engine | Rule + ML hybrid; generates ranked prompts per user; manages delivery channel and timing |
| Notification Service | FCM (Android), APNs (iOS), email; deduplication and throttling |
| Data Store | PostgreSQL (primary), Redis (cache), S3 (raw event archive) |
| ML Platform | SageMaker for model training and serving; A/B testing infrastructure |

## **8.2 Third-Party Dependencies**

| **Provider** | **Purpose** |
| --- | --- |
| Plaid / MX / Finicity | Bank, credit, and investment account aggregation |
| Google OAuth & Microsoft OAuth | Email integration (Gmail, Outlook) |
| AWS (primary cloud) | Compute, storage, ML, CDN |
| Segment | User analytics and event tracking |
| SendGrid | Transactional and notification emails |
| Sentry | Error monitoring and alerting |
| Stripe | Premium subscription billing |
| Braze | Push notification orchestration |

# **9. Monetization Model**

| **Tier** | **Details** |
| --- | --- |
| Basic (Free) | Up to 3 linked accounts, 90-day transaction history, manual categorization, basic cash flow, no email integration |
| Premium ($9.99/month or $79.99/year) | Unlimited accounts, full history, email integration, AI prompts, upcoming expense intelligence, safe-to-spend, investment tracking, priority support |
| Family Plan ($14.99/month) | Up to 5 users on Premium, shared dashboard option for household view |

Future revenue streams (v2+): white-label for financial institutions, referral commissions for high-yield savings / refinancing offers (disclosed and opt-in only), premium financial advisor connection marketplace.

# **10. Roadmap ****&**** Phasing**

## **Phase 1 — MVP (Q2–Q3 2026)**

- Bank, credit card, and investment account aggregation via Plaid

- Transaction ingestion, normalization, and ML categorization

- Dashboard: net worth, account cards, income vs. spend

- Email integration (Gmail first, Outlook in Phase 1b)

- Upcoming expenses detection from email

- Basic cash flow projection (30-day)

- Safe to Spend calculation and display

- Core notification types (bill due, unusual spend, income received)

- iOS and Android app + web

## **Phase 2 — Growth (Q4 2026 – Q1 2027)**

- Loan integration (mortgage, auto, student)

- Pattern-based predicted upcoming expense engine

- Travel & event expense planning (email-sourced itineraries)

- Category spend guardrails and goals

- Investment performance module

- Apple Watch / widget for Safe to Spend

- Family plan

## **Phase 3 — Depth (Q2 2027+)**

- Cryptocurrency wallet integration

- Tax preparation data export (categorized transactions, 1099 detection)

- Debt payoff optimizer (avalanche / snowball modeling)

- In-app financial advisor marketplace

- Savings automation rules ("round up", "sweep excess to savings")

- Open banking API for third-party integrations

# **11. Risks ****&**** Mitigations**

| **Risk** | **Impact** | **Mitigation** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Aggregator API instability or data gaps | Users lose account visibility; trust erodes | Multi-aggregator strategy (Plaid + MX fallback); real-time status page; user-facing error messaging |
| Email permission friction | Low email integration adoption | Strong value-before-ask onboarding; clear, granular privacy controls; visible benefits before prompt |
| ML categorization errors at scale | User frustration; manual correction burden | Confidence thresholds with human review prompts; rapid feedback loop; continuous model retraining |
| Regulatory changes (open banking, data privacy) | Compliance cost or feature rollback required | Legal review at every major feature; modular architecture for regional compliance variants |
| Security breach | Catastrophic trust and reputational damage | Zero-credential storage architecture; bug bounty program; annual pen testing; incident response plan |
| Notification fatigue | Users disable notifications; core loop breaks | Strict daily caps; relevance scoring; A/B testing of timing and copy; easy granular controls |
| Competitive response from incumbents (Mint, YNAB, Copilot) | User acquisition difficulty | Differentiate on email intelligence and proactive prompting; faster iteration cycle |

# **12. Open Questions**

- Which bank aggregator should be the primary provider for MVP — Plaid, MX, or Finicity? Evaluate coverage, pricing, and webhook reliability.

- Should the Safe to Spend model exclude or include credit card available balance? (Risk of encouraging debt spending.)

- What is the minimum viable email integration — full Gmail scan or opt-in per sender/domain?

- Should FinFlow support manual account entry for institutions not covered by aggregators? If so, how do we ensure data quality?

- Legal review needed: Does email transaction matching create any CFPB data aggregator compliance obligations?

- What is the right default notification frequency? Propose A/B test design.

- Should investment performance views be gated behind Premium, or does showing partial data in Free create sufficient upgrade incentive?

# **13. Appendix**

## **13.1 Glossary**

| **Term** | **Definition** |
| --- | --- |
| Safe to Spend | Discretionary amount available after subtracting upcoming fixed expenses and savings buffer from liquid balance |
| Cashflow Projection | Forward-looking estimate of net cash position incorporating income, fixed, and predicted variable expenses |
| Recurring Charge Detection | ML identification of transactions repeating at regular intervals from the same merchant |
| Email Intelligence | NLP-based extraction of financial signals (bills, receipts, bookings) from connected email accounts |
| MQL / SQL | Not applicable in this context — internal abbreviations for financial categories |
| Aggregator | Third-party service (Plaid, MX) that connects FinFlow to financial institutions via their APIs |
| Prompt | A proactive, actionable notification generated by FinFlow's prompt engine based on user financial data |
| Confidence Band | Uncertainty range shown on cashflow projections, widening as prediction horizon increases |

